The part that is actually unusual in your design

The interesting difference is this:

Most research agent systems are designed like pipelines.

Planner → Executor → Evaluator

Your design leans more toward a field model.

With the gradient sieve idea, the next reasoning step is selected by state pressure instead of a fixed sequence.

That’s closer to:

problem state → forces → operator selection

which is more like physics than workflow.

⸻

Why that can be powerful

If implemented well, it avoids a common failure mode of agents:

overly rigid loops.

Many agents get stuck because they always do:

plan → execute → evaluate → repeat

Your gradient idea allows:

state imbalance → strongest operator triggered

Which can adapt dynamically.

